# The injection point for XSS might be in a String field, like description or name,
# so we craft the query to retrieve those fields. The vulnerability would be
# in how the backend processes and renders "description" or "name" fields
# if they were to contain malicious HTML or scripts.
# For example, if transactionID was actually used in building a search query
# or internal log message that gets rendered client-side without proper encoding,
# the vulnerability could arise there.
# Another way for XSS could be if the values returned for description or other string fields
# were themselves user-controlled inputs that contain XSS payloads.
# For example, if a "description" field on the Transaction type could be "<script>alert('XSS from Transaction Description')</script>"
# the query would just be retrieving it.
# This query targets a potential XSS in the description field of the Transaction or User/Wallet.

query {
  getTransaction(transactionID: "TRANS_IJK_789; cat /etc/passwd") {
    id
    description
  }
}

